>
  <article class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-a:text-blue-700 prose-a:underline">
    <p class="kicker">Institutional Documentation</p>
    <h1>Charter of America's School Trust Library</h1>

    <p>
      This charter describes what the Library is, who it serves, who governs
      it, how it makes decisions, how it changes, and how it ends. It is a
      public charter for the Library as an institution. It is not the
      corporate bylaws of the host organization; those live in the records of
      Oregon Advocates for School Trust Lands (OASTL) and govern OASTL as a
      501(c)(3) entity. This charter governs the Library as a project under
      that host.
    </p>

    <h2>Article I — Name and identity</h2>

    <p>
      The institution is named America's School Trust Library. It is hosted
      at schooltrusts.net and was founded in 2026. The Library is presently
      an initiative of Oregon Advocates for School Trust Lands (OASTL), a
      501(c)(3) public-charity nonprofit organized under the laws of the
      State of Oregon. The Library operates under OASTL's fiscal sponsorship
      and uses OASTL's tax status for donations, grants, and contracts. The
      Library is designed to spin out as its own independent 501(c)(3)
      institution when the trigger conditions in Article VIII are met.
    </p>

    <h2>Article II — Purpose</h2>

    <p>
      The Library is an evidentiary archive of America's school trust lands
      and a constituency-formation institution organized around that archive.
    </p>

    <p>
      Its purpose is twofold. First, the Library makes the multi-century,
      multi-jurisdictional record of school trust governance findable and
      usable — for the public, for scholars, for journalists, for trustees,
      for legislators and agency staff, and for the architects of the
      forever-institutions now being designed for the AI era. Second, the
      Library organizes a standing community of contributors — patrons,
      recognized contributors, state co-librarians, and an editorial staff —
      who together sustain that record across generations.
    </p>

    <p>
      The Library treats school trust lands as a national inheritance and a
      working fiduciary experiment that has run long enough to teach lessons
      no other multi-generational trust can yet teach. The Library's work is
      to keep that record honest, accessible, and useful to those who will
      need it.
    </p>

    <h2>Article III — Beneficiaries</h2>

    <p>
      The Library's beneficiaries are the present and future schoolchildren
      of the states, whose claims under the school trust lands are the
      substantive subject of the Library's work. The Library serves their
      interest by keeping the record of how those claims have been honored
      and how they have been breached.
    </p>

    <p>
      The Library is also of operational use to scholars, journalists,
      lawyers, legislators, agency staff, trustees, and the broader public.
      These groups are users; they are not the beneficiaries. Where a user's
      interest and the schoolchildren-beneficiaries' interest diverge, the
      Library's editorial judgment serves the beneficiaries.
    </p>

    <h2>Article IV — Editorial independence</h2>

    <p>
      The Library publishes under its own editorial judgment. OASTL hosts the
      Library as fiscal sponsor and provides corporate, financial, and legal
      infrastructure. OASTL does not approve individual editorial decisions,
      does not direct what the Library publishes or declines to publish, and
      does not control corrections or retractions.
    </p>

    <p>
      Where the Library's record bears on OASTL's own litigation in Oregon,
      the Library reports the same record, by the same standards, that it
      would report for any other state. The Library does not soften Oregon
      coverage to favor OASTL, and it does not sharpen Oregon coverage to
      disfavor adverse parties. Editorial standards — sourcing, attribution,
      correction policy, and conflict-of-interest disclosure — are at
      <a href="/pro/editorial-standards/">/pro/editorial-standards/</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Article V — Officers and decision-making</h2>

    <p>
      The Library is led by a Head Librarian, currently Dave Sullivan, who
      has authority over day-to-day operations and editorial direction. The
      Head Librarian sets editorial policy, approves new content categories,
      oversees corrections, and represents the Library externally.
    </p>

    <p>
      Librarians — currently a small editorial staff — operate the working
      processes of the Library under the Head Librarian's authority. They
      draft and review content, respond to reader feedback, evaluate
      proposed corrections, and steward the relationships with patrons and
      recognized contributors.
    </p>

    <p>
      When the first Library Board is seated under Article VI,
      editorial-policy disputes and substantive corrections that cannot be
      resolved at the librarian or Head Librarian level rise to the Board.
      Until the Board is seated, the Head Librarian is the final editorial
      authority, with the host 501(c)(3) President available as a check on
      conflict-of-interest cases.
    </p>

    <h2>Article VI — The Library Board (planned)</h2>

    <p>
      The Library Board, when seated, will consist of three to five members.
      Members will be appointed by the founding officers — the Head
      Librarian and the President of the host 501(c)(3) — from a public call
      for applications. Terms will be three years, staggered so that no more
      than two seats turn over in any one year. One consecutive renewal will
      be permitted; after a renewed term a member rotates off for at least
      one year before being eligible again.
    </p>

    <p>
      The Board will meet quarterly. Minutes will be published on the
      Library's website within thirty days of each meeting, with personnel
      and donor-confidential matters redacted as needed.
    </p>

    <p>
      Seats will open as funding for staff support permits, beginning with
      the first seat. The Library does not seat a board it cannot support;
      an empty seat is preferred to a seat that exists in name only.
    </p>

    <h2>Article VII — Amendments to this charter</h2>

    <p>
      Amendments to this charter require the approval of the Head Librarian
      and the President of the host 501(c)(3) until the Library Board is
      seated. After the Board is seated, amendments require a majority vote
      of the Board together with the consent of the Head Librarian.
    </p>

    <p>
      Amendments are logged publicly in the adopted-and-amended log at the
      foot of this charter, with the date of the change and a short
      description of its substance. The pre-amendment version of the charter
      is preserved in the Library's own archive so that readers can see what
      changed and when.
    </p>

    <h2>Article VIII — Independence transition</h2>

    <p>
      The Library is designed to outgrow OASTL's host capacity. Spinout to
      an independent 501(c)(3) institution is triggered when all of the
      following conditions are met:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>The Library Board has been seated and has served at least one full three-year term.</li>
      <li>Patron support has reached roughly five thousand active Library Card holders.</li>
      <li>The community of recognized contributors has reached roughly fifty contributors, with at least twenty-five states represented.</li>
      <li>Operating budget has reached a level supporting at least one full-time librarian on the Library's own books.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      When these conditions are met, the transition to an independent
      501(c)(3) is decided jointly by the Library Board and the board of the
      host 501(c)(3). The transition transfers the archive, the brand, the
      patron and contributor relationships, and the editorial staff to the
      new entity, and ends the fiscal-sponsorship relationship with OASTL
      by mutual agreement.
    </p>

    <h2>Article IX — Dissolution</h2>

    <p>
      If the Library is dissolved, its assets — including the archive itself
      — transfer to a successor institution chosen by the Library Board with
      public notice and a reasonable comment period. Absent a willing and
      suitable successor, the archive is donated in trust to the Internet
      Archive or a comparable institutional steward, with a perpetual-access
      requirement attached to the donation.
    </p>

    <p>
      The Library's beneficiaries — the present and future schoolchildren of
      the states — do not lose access to the record by virtue of
      dissolution. Continued public access to the archive is a condition of
      any transfer.
    </p>

    <h2>Adopted and amended</h2>

    <p>Adopted 2026-05-12. No amendments yet.</p>
  </article>

